<ul class="task-constraints">
<li><b>Time limit:</b> 1.00 s</li>
<li><b>Memory limit:</b> 512 MB</li>
</ul>
<input type="hidden" name="course" value="problemset">
<input type="hidden" name="task" value="1698">
You are given an array containing a permutation of numbers $1,2,\dots,n$, and your task is to sort the array using <i>swap rounds</i>. On each swap round, you can choose any number of distinct pairs of elements and swap each pair.<br />
<br />
Your task is to find the minimum number of rounds and show how you can choose the pairs in each round.<br />
<br />
<b id="input">Input</b><br />
<br />
The first input line has an integer $n$: the size of the array.<br />
<br />
The second line has $n$ integers $x_1,x_2,\dots,x_n$: the initial permutation.<br />
<br />
<b id="output">Output</b><br />
<br />
First print an integer $k$: the minimum number of rounds.<br />
<br />
Then, for each round, print the number of swaps and the indices of each swap. You can print any valid solution.<br />
<br />
<b id="constraints">Constraints</b><br />
<ul>
<li> $1 \le n \le 2 \cdot 10^5$<br />
</ul>
<b id="example">Example</b><br />
<br />
Input:<br />
<code>5<br />
5 2 1 3 4</code><br />
<br />
Output:<br />
<code>2<br />
2<br />
1 3<br />
4 5<br />
1<br />
3 5</code><br />
<br />
Explanation: The inital array is $[5,2,1,3,4]$. After round $1$, the array becomes $[1,2,5,4,3]$. After round $2$, the array becomes $[1,2,3,4,5]$.    </div>
